**Abstract:**
Major essay titled "Christianity is not a Doctrine" opening with quotations from Kierkegaard and Lonergan. Develops thesis that Christianity was wrongly conceived as doctrine requiring assent. Extensive quotations from Charles Taylor on quality of will in moral philosophy, Hans Frei on biblical narratives, Levinas on ethics as first philosophy. Analyzes Pyrrhonian skepticism, Nietzsche, and truth as correspondence. Argues all perception is applicative and practical knowledge has primacy.

**AI Recommendation:** Major book chapter; see 99-aug-1-1 variant. Central theoretical text.

